Ho-Chunk Nation of Wisconsin,HoChunkNation,"U.S. Dept. of Interior, FWS Great Lakes-Big Rivers Region",Illinois,La Salle,Near Ottawa,Seizure Tag #: 745803,1,0,"In the 1920s, human remains representing one individual were removed from the unspecified site near Ottawa,  la Salle County, IL. U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service agents seized the human remains as part of an investigation of illegal trafficking of Native American human remains [18 U.S.C. 1170 (a)]. Subsequent examination by an anthropologist and testting of the human remains revealed that they are of an approximately 24-year-old Native American female that lived sometime between A.D. 1030 and 1290. On July 25th, 2002, U.S. District Court Magistrate Judge Nan R. Nolan ordered that control of the human remains be transferred to the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service for purposes of repatriation.",A.D. 1030 and 1290,,culturally affiliated with the Ho-Chunk Nation of Wisconsin and Winnebago Tribe of Nebraska. Repatriated in 2005.

Ho-Chunk Nation of Wisconsin,HoChunkNation,"Univ. of Wisconsin, Stevens Point",Wisconsin,Portage,Bigelow-Hamilton (47-Pr-29),N/A,2,71,"In the late 1950s, human remains were removed fromm the Bigelow-Hamilton site (47-Pr-29), Portage County, WI, by George Dixon. Mr. Dixon subsequently donated the human remains and associated funerary objects to the University of Wisconsin-Stevens Point. No known individuals were identified. Most of the human remains and associated funerary objects were reinterred in 1986 and 1987 at the request of the Wisconsin Winnebago Tribe, now called the Ho-Chunk Nation of Wisconsin. In 1994, 1995, and 2001, additional human remains representing a minimum of two individuals and associated funerary objects from  the Bigelow-Hamilton site were discovered in the University of Wisconsin-Stevens Point collections.",,"1 fragment of mink or otter fur, 2 textile fragments, 9 shell fragments, 6 stone tools, 48 stone flakes, 3 Madison Plain sherds, and 2 cord-impressed sherds.",

Menominee Indian Tribe of Wisconsin,Menominee,Univ. of Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology,Michigan,Unknown,Unknown,Cat #: L-606-0454,1,0,"At an unknown date between 1820 and 1837, human remains representing, at minimum, one individual (UPM #: 97-606-454) were removed from an unknown site in Michigan or Wisconsin by Dr. Richard S. Satterlee, Assistant Surgeon for the U.S. Army. In this capacity, Dr. Satterlee served at the Detroit Barracks, MI, Fort Howard, WI, Fort Mackinac, MI, Fort Winnebago, WI, and for a second term at Fort Howard, WI. The human remains were transferred to Dr. Samuel Morton in Philadelphia for inclusion in his collection of human crania from around the world prior to 1839. Menominee Indian Tribe of Wisconsin,Menominee,Oshkosh Public Museum,Wisconsin,Winnebago,Robert Grignon Trading Post Site (47-Wn-137),Catalog #: ANNEXS23B,1,0,"Circa 1936, human remains representing one individual were removed from the Robert Grignon Trading Post Site (47-Wn-137), Winnebago, WI by Oshkosh Public Museum staff Arthur Kannenberg. Documentation indicates that the tombstone that marked this burial identified the remains as those of ""Mary/wife of/Robert Grignon/died Dec 24, 1851/age/37 years"". The remains were, reportedly, re-buried inn the same grave except for two vertebrae and two teeth that are now in the possession of the Oshkosh Public Museum. A contemporaneous accound of the excavation of the grave identified Mary Grignon as the daughter of a full-blodded Menominee chief. Other historical sources indicate that her Menominee name is Wak-nau-go-lak.",,,published in FR 10/25/2000 culturally affiliated with the Menominee Indian Tribe of WI

Menominee Indian Tribe of Wisconsin,Menominee,"U.S. Dept.of Interior, BIA",Wisconsin,Menominee,Menominee Indian Reservation in Keshena,N/A,1,20,"In 1926, Oshkosh Public Museum staff Arthur Kannenberg excavated the graves of two individuals located on the Menominee Indian Reservation in Keshena, WI. The remains of one individual, believed to have been those of Chief Oshkosh, were re-interred at a new location in Oshkosh, WI shortly thereafter. The remains of the second individual, believed to have been those of one of Chief Oshkosh's wives, were not re-located. Two cervical vertebrae were removed from one of the two graves and donated to the Oshkosh Public Museum by an unknown person, presumably Mr. Kannenberg, at an unknown time after 1926. An unknown person, presumably Mr. Kannenberg, retained remnants of Chief Oshkosh's original casket, including pieces of glass, metal, cloth, wood, beads, three nails, and scraps of beaded cloth. These nine funerary objects were donated to the Oshkosh Public Museum, presumably by Mr. Kannenberg, at an unknown time between 1926-1945. At an unknown time, but presumably during the 1926 exhumation, 11 funerary objects consisting of a wooden spool, 8 buttons, shears, and 1 nail were collected from the grave of a wife of Chief Oshkosh. They were donated to the Oshkosh Public Museum by an unknown person, but presumed to be Mr. Kannenberg, at an unknown time between 1926-1945.",,"pieces of glass, metal, cloth, wood, beads, three nails, and scraps of beaded cloth",published inn FR 10/25/2000 culturally affiliated with Menominee Indian Tribe of Wisconsin. Repatriated in 2001

column1: Ho-Chunk Nation,HoChunkNation,"Univ. of Iowa, Office of the State Archaeologist",Iowa,Lyon,13LO2,Accession #: Burial Project 2891,2,0,"13LO2, the Blood Run National Historic Landmark site, is a known Oneota site locatin in northwest Lyon County, Iowa. Amy Harvey received her doctorate degree from the University of Wisconsin-Madison in the 1960s. Her doctoral research focused on Oneota sites in Iowa, including 13LO2. In 1965, she took a teaching position with Stephens College in Columbia, Missouri. The collections she used for her doctoral research went with her to Stephens College, and she accumulated other collections from numerous sites in Iowa and Missouri during her career. Harvey died in 1998. The University of Iowa Office of the State Archaeologist (OSA) initiated attempts to locate Harvey’s Iowa collections in the mid-1990s but was unsuccessful until 2010. The human skeletal remains from 13LO2 had been stored at Stephens College in Columbia, Missouri. They were transferred to the OSA Burials Program in 2010. Materials from 13LO2, had been in the collections transferred to the OSA in 2010 (OSA 2013a). Harvey had been involved in archaeological excavations at 13LO2 in 1964 through the University of Wisconsin-Madison (Harvey 1971, 1979).
